VALUES
(43, 8, 23, 45, 8, 7, 8, 'I am from above', 'Connection of Worldly vs. Spiritual', 'Both passages emphasize the distinction between the spiritual and the carnal. John 8:23 highlights being ''from above'' versus ''this world,'' while Romans 8:7-8 discusses the enmity of the carnal mind against God, reinforcing the idea that those in the flesh cannot please God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 24, 43, 3, 36, 36, 'believe not that I am he', 'Connection of Belief and Consequences', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of belief in Jesus. John 8:24 warns that those who do not believe will die in their sins, while John 3:36 states that those who do not believe will not see life and face God''s wrath.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 24, 41, 16, 16, 16, NULL, 'Connection of Belief and Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of belief for salvation. John 8:24 warns that those who do not believe will die in their sins, while Mark 16:16 states that belief is essential for salvation, linking belief directly to one''s eternal fate.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 24, 43, 3, 18, 18, 'believe not that I am he', 'Condemnation and Belief Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief and its consequences. Both passages emphasize that belief in Jesus is essential to avoid condemnation and death in sin.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 24, 58, 10, 26, 29, 'ye shall die in your sins', 'Consequences of Unbelief and Sin', 'This connection highlights the severe consequences of unbelief and willful sin. Both passages emphasize that failing to believe in Jesus leads to dire spiritual repercussions, including judgment and a lack of sacrifice for sins.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 24, 58, 12, 25, 25, 'ye shall die in your sins', 'Consequences of Refusal', 'Both passages emphasize the dire consequences of not believing or refusing the one who speaks. John 8:24 warns of dying in sins without belief, while Hebrews 12:25 warns of not escaping if one turns away from the heavenly speaker.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 24, 20, 8, 36, 36, 'die in your sins', 'Connection of Sin and Death', 'This connection highlights the consequences of sin, as both passages emphasize that rejecting truth leads to death. John 8:24 warns of dying in sins, while Proverbs 8:36 states that those who sin against wisdom love death.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 24, 44, 4, 12, 12, 'ye shall die in your sins', 'Salvation and Belief Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of belief for salvation. John 8:24 indicates that belief in Jesus is essential to avoid dying in sins, while Acts 4:12 states that salvation is found only in His name.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 25, 43, 5, 17, 29, 'Even the same that I said unto you', 'Connection of Identity and Authority', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' divine identity and authority. In John 8:25, Jesus asserts his consistent identity, while in John 5:17-29, he explains his relationship with the Father, highlighting his role in judgment and life-giving power.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 25, 42, 22, 67, 67, 'Who art thou?', 'Identity of Jesus as Christ', 'This connection highlights the question of Jesus'' identity in both passages. In John 8:25, Jesus asserts his consistent identity, while in Luke 22:67, the inquiry about him being the Christ reflects the same theme of recognition and belief.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 25, 43, 1, 22, 22, 'Who art thou?', 'Identity Inquiry of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the question, ''Who art thou?'' directed at Jesus, highlighting the ongoing inquiry into his identity. This connection illustrates the consistent theme of Jesus revealing himself throughout the Gospel of John.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 25, 43, 8, 12, 12, 'Even the same that I said unto you from the beginning', 'Connection of Identity and Light', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' assertion of his identity as he states, ''Even the same that I said unto you from the beginning,'' which relates to his declaration, ''I am the light of the world.'' Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus'' role in providing spiritual illumination.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 25, 43, 19, 9, 9, 'Who art thou?', 'Identity and Origin of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the inquiry into Jesus'' identity in both passages. In John 8:25, Jesus asserts his consistent identity, while in John 19:9, the question of his origin is posed, reflecting a similar theme of seeking to understand who Jesus is.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 26, 43, 15, 15, 15, 'those things which I have heard of him', 'Revelation of Divine Knowledge', 'Both passages emphasize the sharing of knowledge from God. In John 8:26, Jesus speaks of what he has heard from the Father, while in John 15:15, he reveals that he has made known all things heard from the Father to his friends.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 26, 43, 8, 40, 40, NULL, 'Truth and Revelation Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of truth as revealed by God. In John 8:26, Jesus speaks of the truth he has heard from God, while in John 8:40, he highlights that he has told the truth he received from God, contrasting himself with Abraham.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 26, 43, 12, 47, 50, 'he that sent me is true', 'Judgment and Commandment Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Father in Jesus'' words and judgment. John 8:26 mentions speaking what He has heard from the Father, while John 12:49-50 reiterates that His commandment comes from the Father, linking their messages about judgment and divine authority.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 26, 43, 7, 28, 28, 'he that sent me is true', 'Connection of Truth and Sending', 'Both passages emphasize the truth of the one who sent Jesus. In John 8:26, Jesus speaks of the one who sent him as true, paralleling John 7:28 where he states that the one who sent him is true.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 26, 47, 1, 18, 18, 'he that sent me is true', 'Truth in Communication', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of truth in communication. John speaks of the truth of the one who sent him, while Paul asserts that God''s truth underlies their message.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 26, 58, 5, 11, 12, 'many things to say', 'Teaching and Understanding', 'This connection highlights the theme of teaching and understanding in both passages. John 8:26 speaks of the need to convey truths heard from God, while Hebrews 5:11-12 addresses the need for deeper understanding and maturity in teaching.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 27, 23, 6, 9, 9, 'understood not that he spake', 'Understanding and Perception', 'Both passages emphasize a lack of understanding among the people. In John 8:27, the people do not grasp that Jesus speaks of the Father, paralleling Isaiah 6:9, where the people hear but do not understand.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 27, 23, 42, 18, 20, 'understood not that he spake', 'Blindness and Deafness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize a lack of understanding and perception. John 8:27 highlights the failure to comprehend Jesus'' message about the Father, while Isaiah 42:18-20 addresses the blindness and deafness of God''s servant, illustrating a similar theme of spiritual blindness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 27, 43, 8, 43, 43, 'understood not that he spake to them', 'Understanding and Hearing Jesus'' Words', 'This connection highlights the theme of understanding in both passages. In John 8:27, the lack of understanding about the Father is echoed in John 8:43, where the inability to hear His word is emphasized.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 27, 45, 11, 7, 10, 'understood not that he spake to them', 'Spiritual Blindness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of spiritual blindness. In John 8:27, the lack of understanding about the Father reflects a deeper spiritual blindness, which is further articulated in Romans 11:7-10, where Israel is described as having been blinded. This connection highlights a shared concern about the inability to perceive divine truth.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 27, 47, 4, 3, 4, 'understood not that he spake', 'Understanding and Spiritual Blindness', 'This connection highlights the theme of misunderstanding spiritual truths. In John 8:27, the lack of understanding about the Father parallels 2 Corinthians 4:3-4, where the minds of the lost are blinded from recognizing the gospel''s light.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 28, 43, 5, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Action', 'Both passages emphasize that the Son can do nothing of himself, highlighting the dependence of Jesus on the Father for His actions and teachings.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 28, 43, 5, 30, 30, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Dependence', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' reliance on the Father. They highlight that he does nothing of himself and seeks the Father''s will.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 28, 40, 27, 50, 54, 'that I am he', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Identity', 'This connection highlights the moment of recognition of Jesus as the Son of God. In John 8:28, Jesus indicates that his true identity will be revealed after his crucifixion, which is affirmed in Matthew 27:54 when the centurion declares, ''Truly this was the Son of God.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 28, 45, 1, 4, 4, 'Son of man', 'Connection of Sonship and Resurrection', 'This connection highlights the declaration of Jesus'' identity as the Son of God, which is affirmed in both passages. John 8:28 speaks of Jesus being ''lifted up,'' while Romans 1:4 emphasizes his power through resurrection, linking his identity and divine authority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 28, 52, 2, 15, 16, 'lifted up the Son of man', 'Connection of Persecution and Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of Jesus and the consequences of that rejection. John 8:28 speaks of recognition of Jesus after his crucifixion, while 1 Thessalonians 2:15-16 addresses the persecution of Jesus and his followers, highlighting the ongoing consequences for those who oppose him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 28, 4, 16, 28, 30, 'I do nothing of myself', 'Authority and Divine Sending', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority in both passages. Jesus asserts that he speaks as taught by the Father, while Moses claims he does not act on his own mind, emphasizing their roles as messengers of God.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
